│ THOUGHT: The remaining failing test expects that when a global has atomic pointer accesses, GlobalOpt should not perform the malloc-promotion that introduces the synthesized init flag. │
│ To address this robustly and avoid generating any i1 init flag or changing IR in atomic scenarios, I will add an early bail-out in OptimizeGlobalAddressOfAllocation: after collecting   │
│ uses, if any load/store to the global is atomic, skip the optimization. This prevents the pass from introducing non-byte-sized atomic operations and aligns with test expectations.      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i 's/allUsesOfLoadAndStores(GV, Guses);/allUsesOfLoadAndStores(GV, Guses);\n  for (auto *U : Guses) {\n    if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(U)) {\n      if (SI->isAtomic())      │
│ return nullptr;\n    } else if (auto *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(U)) {\n      if (LI->isAtomic()) return nullptr;\n    }\n  }/' llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp                       │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
