│ THOUGHT: The failing test shows GlobalOpt still promotes the malloc to a global body (@g.body) even when the uses of @g are atomic, which changes IR unexpectedly. To fix, we should     │
│ bail out of OptimizeGlobalAddressOfAllocation before any transformation when any load/store to the global is atomic. I will insert an early atomic-uses check right before the           │
│ allocation promotion begins (before the creation of the new global body), ensuring the optimization is skipped entirely in atomic scenarios.                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i '/Type \*GlobalType = ArrayType::get(Type::getInt8Ty(GV->getContext),/i \  // Early bail-out: skip malloc promotion if any use of the global is atomic.\n  for (User *U :         │
│ GV->users()) {\n    if (auto *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(U)) { if (LI->isAtomic()) return nullptr; }\n    if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(U)) { if (SI->isAtomic()) return nullptr; }\n  │
│ }\n' llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp                                                                                                                                               │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
